why we should use the cloud.

51
00:02:20,150 --> 00:02:23,230
So "The cloud excels at
two ends of the spectrum.

52
00:02:23,230 --> 00:02:25,900
The first end is when your
application is so simple and low

53
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:28,390
traffic that you really do
save on complexity by starting

54
00:02:28,390 --> 00:02:29,960
with fully managed services.

55
00:02:29,960 --> 00:02:32,240
The second is when your
load is highly irregular,

56
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:35,060
when you have wild swings or
towering peaks and usages,

57
00:02:35,060 --> 00:02:37,630
when the baseline is a
sliver of your largest needs,

58
00:02:37,630 --> 00:02:42,250
or when you have no idea whether
you need 10 servers or 100."

59
00:02:42,250 --> 00:02:44,200
So that, I think,
really summarizes

60
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:46,720
what we've talked
about this semester.

61
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:49,060
How do we build tools
and applications

62
00:02:49,060 --> 00:02:53,075
that scale with wildly
different needs and usages?

63
00:02:53,075 --> 00:02:55,450
And so I want you to think,
what are some businesses that

64
00:02:55,450 --> 00:02:57,130
fall into that
first category, that

65
00:02:57,130 --> 00:03:00,370
fall into the side of things
where maybe your application is

66
00:03:00,370 --> 00:03:01,353
so simple?

67
00:03:01,353 --> 00:03:03,770
Really, you're not worried
about the big swings and usages

68
00:03:03,770 --> 00:03:04,270
right now.

69
00:03:04,270 --> 00:03:06,438
You're just saying, I
have a simple product.

70
00:03:06,438 --> 00:03:07,730
What are some examples of that?

71
00:03:07,730 --> 00:03:10,600
Maybe pause and
think about that.

72
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:14,420
I know what I'll say is that I
think about a tool like Heroku.

73
00:03:14,420 --> 00:03:17,690
Heroku allowed us to build
our flask application.

74
00:03:17,690 --> 00:03:20,300
And with one or two
lines on the terminal,

75
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:22,840
we could push our
app to run live.

76
00:03:22,840 --> 00:03:24,265
