00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:29,430
and whatnot, or
need more capacity.

491
00:20:29,430 --> 00:20:31,530
But your laptop itself
doesn't really matter.

492
00:20:31,530 --> 00:20:34,160
This is just going
to be whatever you

493
00:20:34,160 --> 00:20:35,860
need to use on a daily basis.

494
00:20:35,860 --> 00:20:38,270
Sorry, my dog just walked in.

495
00:20:38,270 --> 00:20:41,030
And so that's kind of the
idea behind the Remote Desktop

496
00:20:41,030 --> 00:20:43,610
protocol.

497
00:20:43,610 --> 00:20:46,280
And so then going on
to the hypervisor,

498
00:20:46,280 --> 00:20:48,390
so the hypervisor is--

499
00:20:48,390 --> 00:20:52,170
again, like I said, this is a
much more how Amazon does it

500
00:20:52,170 --> 00:20:53,980
with their EC2 instances.

501
00:20:53,980 --> 00:20:57,670
So these EC2 instances
sit on some hardware.

502
00:20:57,670 --> 00:20:59,520
The hardware is
the server itself.

503
00:20:59,520 --> 00:21:02,310
And then the hypervisor
allocates the resources

504
00:21:02,310 --> 00:21:04,030
to the individual users.

505
00:21:04,030 --> 00:21:07,000
And really, the hypervisor is
providing an operating system,

506
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:09,752
a full-on operating
system, to that user,

507
00:21:09,752 --> 00:21:11,460
such that, again, they
could SSH into it,

508
00:21:11,460 --> 00:21:14,770
or you could even have them do a
Remote Desktop connection to it.

509
00:21:14,770 --> 00:21:16,600
But it's being managed by this.

510
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:19,800
So you're basically giving
them virtual hardware access.

511
00:21:19,800 --> 00:21:22,500
And so there's two types of
these, not really important

512
00:21:22,500 --> 00:21:23,675
for this class.

513
00:21:23,675 --> 00:21:25,050
But just so you
know that you can

514
00:21:25,050 --> 00:21:29,220
have type 1 hypervisors
that operate directly

515
00:21:29,220 --> 00:21:30,670
on the hardware level.

516
00:21:30,670 --> 00:21:33,090
So they sit just
above the hardware

517
00:21:33,090 --> 00:21:35,800
before the operating
system is even in place.

518
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:38,880
They are allocating the
operating system to the users.

519
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:41,370
And that usually has
speed, latency benefits,

520
00:21:41,370 --> 00:21:45,420
and all that good
stuff, and also

521
00:21:45,420 --> 00:21:46,780
just is a lighter weight, too.

522
00:21:46,780 --> 00:21:48,550
I don't have to have
as much software.

523
00:21:48,550 --> 00:21:51,613
I'm not limited on what
hypervisor can use,

524
00:21:51,613 --> 00:21:54,030
or better statement, I'm not
limited on what the operating

525
00:21:54,030 --> 00:21:56,363
system has available to it,
since I'm operating directly

526
00:21:56,363 --> 00:21:57,150
on the hardware.

527
00:21:57,150 --> 00:21:59,800
Type 2 is sitting on
an operating system.

528
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:01,300
So there exists an
operating system.

529
00:22:01,300 --> 00:22:03,160
So this is like me running
Windows on my computer,

530
00:22:03,160 --> 00:22:05,370
then having a hypervisor
that's running on my Windows

531
00:22:05,370 --> 00:22:09,135
machine, that then is allocating
operating systems to the user.

532
00:22:09,135 --> 00:22:11,010
And these operating
systems don't necessarily

533
00:22:11,010 --> 00:22:13,740
have to be the same as
this base operating system.

534
00:22:13,740 --> 00:22:16,740
It just depends on whatever your
architecture and the hypervisor

535
00:22:16,740 --> 00:22:17,650
supports.

536
00:22:17,650 --> 00:22:20,503
But this now is an,
or better statement,

537
00:22:20,503 --> 00:22:21,670
this is just an alternative.

538
00:22:21,670 --> 00:22:24,520
And there are just more
type 2 than type 1.

539
00:22:24,520 --> 00:22:29,280
But there is even a type I
open source hypervisor called

540
00:22:29,280 --> 00:22:30,010
Xen Project.

541
00:22:30,010 --> 00:22:31,750
It's part of the
Linux Foundation.

542
00:22:31,750 --> 00:22:34,300
And so again, you
could download--

543
00:22:34,300 --> 00:22:36,540
you could have your
own server at home.

544
00:22:36,540 --> 00:22:38,230
You could download
this hypervisor,

545
00:22:38,230 --> 00:22:40,170
run this hypervisor
on that server

546
00:22:40,170 --> 00:22:42,790
and allocate your resources
to all the users in your home.

547
00:22:42,790 --> 00:22:46,420
So maybe your family has
varying compute needs.

548
00:22:46,420 --> 00:22:48,640
And so you could
build a home server

549
00:22:48,640 --> 00:22:50,680
that allocates
resources as necessary

550
00:22:50,680 --> 00:22:54,460
or as requested by your
family to use on the--

551
00:22:54,460 --> 00:22:56,330
or to use those
different computers.

552
00:22:59,180 --> 00:23:01,080
And that brings me
to the next one.

553
00:23:01,080 --> 00:23:02,165
So these are more--

554
00:23:02,165 --> 00:23:04,040
this is just a little
bit more of a fun idea.

555
00:23:04,040 --> 00:23:06,990
It's a little bit different from
what we've been talking about.

556
00:23:06,990 --> 00:23:10,890
But this idea of home-labbing
is growing pretty significantly.

557
00:23:10,890 --> 00:23:13,560
And the exact idea
behind this is just, hey,

558
00:23:13,560 --> 00:23:19,390
what if I built my own cloud
computing platform at home?

559
00:23:19,390 --> 00:23:21,890
What if I had my
own cloud at home?

560
00:23:21,890 --> 00:23:25,890
And all these images are pulled
from the r/HomeLab subreddit.

561
00:23:25,890 --> 00:23:29,120
So you can check that out if
you're interested in this topic

562
00:23:29,120 --> 00:23:29,880
at all.

563
00:23:29,880 --> 00:23:33,890
And it does require, again,
a lot of hardware experience,

564
00:23:33,890 --> 00:23:35,940
and costs can get
really expensive.

565
00:23:35,940 --> 00:23:37,530
But they can also stay low, too.

566
00:23:37,530 --> 00:23:39,470
Right here, this on the
bottom right hand side

567
00:23:39,470 --> 00:23:44,160
is a set of four Raspberry Pis
running as a Kubernetes cluster.

568
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:45,680
So serving-- you can basically--

569
00:23:45,680 --> 00:23:49,380
Kubernetes is a container
orchestration service.

570
00:23:49,380 --> 00:23:52,730
And so I could have
my Docker containers,

571
00:23:52,730 --> 00:23:54,800
a bunch of Docker
applications that

572
00:23:54,800 --> 00:23:58,590
could run directly off
of this cluster here.

573
00:23:58,590 --> 00:24:00,522
It just has cooling
pipes coming into it.

574
00:24:00,522 --> 00:24:01,980
So it's a pretty
cool little setup.

575
00:24:01,980 --> 00:24:04,272
It wouldn't cost you too
much, assuming you could get--

576
00:24:04,272 --> 00:24:06,600
Raspberry Pis are a little
hard to find these days.

577
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:09,183
But assuming you get those, you
could do this for really cheap

578
00:24:09,183 --> 00:24:11,740
and have technically your
own little server at home.

579
00:24:11,740 --> 00:24:15,750
This is a cloud computing
cluster connected

580
00:24:15,750 --> 00:24:16,900
to your internet network.

581
00:24:16,900 --> 00:24:19,540
It has high-speed connections
running between any of these.

582
00:24:19,540 --> 00:24:21,707
So they're all going to be
able to share information

583
00:24:21,707 --> 00:24:22,530
very quickly.

584
00:24:22,530 --> 00:24:24,810
And so you can have
a full-on server

585
00:24:24,810 --> 00:24:27,390
just from this little thing,
or you could get really intense

586
00:24:27,390 --> 00:24:29,500
and have a big server rack here.

587
00:24:29,500 --> 00:24:32,220
And this is a diagram of
some of these smart home

588
00:24:32,220 --> 00:24:33,730
setup that's all based on this.

589
00:24:33,730 --> 00:24:35,460
And that's one of
the common use cases

590
00:24:35,460 --> 00:24:38,850
for home lab setups is
just smart home management.

591
00:24:38,850 --> 00:24:40,690
But you can use it as
a home media server.

592
00:24:40,690 --> 00:24:43,270
So if you have a bunch of
movies, and photos, and stuff,

593
00:24:43,270 --> 00:24:48,040
well, rather than me paying
for S3 cloud storage,

594
00:24:48,040 --> 00:24:50,917
I could just buy the
physical storage space here,

595
00:24:50,917 --> 00:24:53,500
manage it myself, and I could
have all my Google Photos there.

596
00:24:53,500 --> 00:24:54,880
I can have an
internet connected.

597
00:24:54,880 --> 00:24:56,547
And so rather than
having Google Photos,

598
00:24:56,547 --> 00:24:59,770
I just have my photos folders
which are internet connected.

599
00:24:59,770 --> 00:25:02,680
I can access them from my phone,
my laptop, whatever I want.

600
00:25:02,680 --> 00:25:05,280
And yeah, it'll require
a lot of effort on my end

601
00:25:05,280 --> 00:25:07,060
and probably cost on my end.

602
00:25:07,060 --> 00:25:09,010
But it's also non-trivial.

603
00:25:09,010 --> 00:25:12,130
It's not cheap to have
cloud resources either.

604
00:25:12,130 --> 00:25:14,970
And so it's, just again, depends
on what your interests are.

605
00:25:14,970 --> 00:25:17,220
It's not to say that everybody
or anybody really needs

606
00:25:17,220 --> 00:25:19,252
to build a full home lab setup.

607
00:25:19,252 --> 00:25:21,460
But if you are interested
in the hardware side of it,

608
00:25:21,460 --> 00:25:22,930
it's kind of a fun way to do it.

609
00:25:22,930 --> 00:25:24,787
It's a really great
resume booster.

610
00:25:24,787 --> 00:25:27,120
You can talk about what you've
actually done, how you've

611
00:25:27,120 --> 00:25:28,500
actually built server racks.

612
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:30,640
I think that'll impress
some companies, for sure.

613
00:25:30,640 --> 00:25:34,920
So that's out there as far as--
and I also provided a few links

614
00:25:34,920 --> 00:25:37,650
as far as other things you
can do with them and some more

615
00:25:37,650 --> 00:25:38,350
resources.

616
00:25:38,350 --> 00:25:40,570
But the moral of
the story is, again,

617
00:25:40,570 --> 00:25:46,560
that the tools to do what we
do in the cloud, the aspects

618
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:49,180
of those tools, we can
do those ourselves.

619
00:25:49,180 --> 00:25:50,890
There exist open
source alternatives.

620
00:25:50,890 --> 00:25:52,682
And for that matter,
as you continue

621
00:25:52,682 --> 00:25:55,140
to build your education, you
can start to build these tools

622
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:57,390
and really, again,
build a different type

623
00:25:57,390 --> 00:25:59,047
of internet for yourself.

624
00:25:59,047 --> 00:26:01,380
It's not to say there's
anything wrong with the internet

625
00:26:01,380 --> 00:26:05,490
today, right or wrong, but it's
just that I want you always

626
00:26:05,490 --> 00:26:07,680
to remain open to the
different opportunities that

627
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:09,360
may exist out there.

628
00:26:09,360 --> 00:26:12,720
It's always hard to
say on the outset what

629
00:26:12,720 --> 00:26:15,430
the next iteration of the
internet is going to look like.

630
00:26:15,430 --> 00:26:19,860
But it's important to stay open
to new ideas and new potentials

631
00:26:19,860 --> 00:26:21,270
for the future.

632
00:26:21,270 --> 00:26:24,250
And so that kind of brings
us then to this big picture.

633
00:26:24,250 --> 00:26:28,180
So one more quote from that
article that I mentioned before.

634
00:26:28,180 --> 00:26:30,438
But they said, "But this
isn't just about cost.

635
00:26:30,438 --> 00:26:31,980
It's also about what
kind of internet

636
00:26:31,980 --> 00:26:33,370
we want to operate
in the future.

637
00:26:33,370 --> 00:26:34,620
It strikes me as
downright tragic

638
00:26:34,620 --> 00:26:36,210
that this decentralized
wonder of the world

639
00:26:36,210 --> 00:26:38,002
is now largely operating
on computers owned

640
00:26:38,002 --> 00:26:39,820
by a handful of corporations.

641
00:26:39,820 --> 00:26:42,160
If one of the primary
AWS regions goes down,

642
00:26:42,160 --> 00:26:44,370
seemingly half the internet
is offline with it.

643
00:26:44,370 --> 00:26:46,230
This is not what
DARPA designed."

644
00:26:46,230 --> 00:26:48,360
And they're not
wrong, to some extent.

645
00:26:48,360 --> 00:26:51,780
We've all experienced
this whenever

646
00:26:51,780 --> 00:26:55,650
all of a sudden, Netflix doesn't
work. amazon.com doesn't work.

647
00:26:55,650 --> 00:26:57,870
Twitter, Facebook,
all these sites

648
00:26:57,870 --> 00:27:00,160
go down that we access daily.

649
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:03,060
And it feels like, what happened
that half of the internet

650
00:27:03,060 --> 00:27:04,080
just shut off then?

651
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:06,048
To some extent, it's
because we have heavily

652
00:27:06,048 --> 00:27:07,090
centralized our internet.

653
00:27:07,090 --> 00:27:09,660
I think the last time I looked
something like 30-something

654
00:27:09,660 --> 00:27:12,960
percent of internet traffic
is running through AWS.

655
00:27:12,960 --> 00:27:14,760
And the rest of
it being allocated

656
00:27:14,760 --> 00:27:17,490
to the other major cloud
providers for the most part.

657
00:27:17,490 --> 00:27:20,430
And so this is the
big consideration

658
00:27:20,430 --> 00:27:23,580
is, what does that mean for
us, both from a standpoint

659
00:27:23,580 --> 00:27:28,620
of a usability, but
also then opportunity?

660
00:27:28,620 --> 00:27:31,680
What does the
centralized internet

661
00:27:31,680 --> 00:27:34,650
allow that a potential
decentralized internet doesn't

662
00:27:34,650 --> 00:27:35,790
allow?

663
00:27:35,790 --> 00:27:37,870
So yeah, I want you
to think about this.

664
00:27:37,870 --> 00:27:40,135
And these three
questions, I really

665
00:27:40,135 --> 00:27:41,260
don't have answers to them.

666
00:27:41,260 --> 00:27:42,885
So I'm not going to
be able to give you

667
00:27:42,885 --> 00:27:45,550
the nice, clean-cut
lecture answer to these.

668
00:27:45,550 --> 00:27:48,180
But what are the downsides
of centralizing internet

669
00:27:48,180 --> 00:27:49,600
to a few large players?

670
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:52,320
What are some of the blockers to
actually decentralizing, then,

671
00:27:52,320 --> 00:27:54,130
if we prefer to go
the other direction,

672
00:27:54,130 --> 00:27:55,870
and they are easier to overcome?

673
00:27:55,870 --> 00:27:59,830
And I think those two questions
are the fundamental question

674
00:27:59,830 --> 00:28:02,020
to at least how the
infrastructure of the internet

675
00:28:02,020 --> 00:28:03,482
will look in the near future.

676
00:28:03,482 --> 00:28:05,440
Because these are the
two major decisions that,

677
00:28:05,440 --> 00:28:08,770
or the two major things we've
been playing with in industry

678
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:12,170
is centralizing heavily
to a few major players,

679
00:28:12,170 --> 00:28:17,110
streamlines things, make sure
or ensures interoperability,

680
00:28:17,110 --> 00:28:22,420
but comes at the cost of are at
the will of the large players.

681
00:28:22,420 --> 00:28:26,000
And also, does it
reduce the opportunity?

682
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:29,140
Does it reduce the
ingenuity, the inventiveness

683
00:28:29,140 --> 00:28:31,420
of all the technologies
we have out there?

684
00:28:31,420 --> 00:28:34,790
Does it constrain us to
only build what Amazon has,

685
00:28:34,790 --> 00:28:36,580
allowing us to build.

686
00:28:36,580 --> 00:28:39,250
All these kind of things, I
think, just really open up

687
00:28:39,250 --> 00:28:40,670
more opportunities.

688
00:28:40,670 --> 00:28:43,270
And that's where I
think the major benefit

689
00:28:43,270 --> 00:28:45,775
of the decentralizing
of the internet is,

690
00:28:45,775 --> 00:28:49,930
is that it opens up the
door to every small player

691
00:28:49,930 --> 00:28:54,460
in the space to build a new,
interesting, innovative tool

692
00:28:54,460 --> 00:28:56,410
that didn't really
exist or couldn't really

693
00:28:56,410 --> 00:28:59,300
exist with a heavily
centralized internet.

694
00:28:59,300 --> 00:29:01,090
But I think the major
downsides, then,

695
00:29:01,090 --> 00:29:03,250
are the difficulties
are, well, how

696
00:29:03,250 --> 00:29:05,090
do we ensure interoperability?

697
00:29:05,090 --> 00:29:07,000
How do I ensure that
I can easily discover

698
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:08,810
and manage and support.

699
00:29:08,810 --> 00:29:10,435
How do I ensure
that it's equitable?

700
00:29:10,435 --> 00:29:12,310
How do I ensure that we
have equitable access

701
00:29:12,310 --> 00:29:14,298
to cloud computing resources?

702
00:29:14,298 --> 00:29:16,090
We talked a bit about
this at the beginning

703
00:29:16,090 --> 00:29:18,740
that Amazon's not
perfect either at this,

704
00:29:18,740 --> 00:29:21,430
but at least, they
have the resources

705
00:29:21,430 --> 00:29:24,680
to leverage the economies of
scale, and all that good stuff.

706
00:29:24,680 --> 00:29:27,520
So I don't know if there's
a clear-cut answer to which

707
00:29:27,520 --> 00:29:29,330
direction things will go.

708
00:29:29,330 --> 00:29:32,380
But I want you to be open
and explore opportunities

709
00:29:32,380 --> 00:29:34,638
in either direction.

710
00:29:34,638 --> 00:29:36,430
One interesting one
that's been in the news

711
00:29:36,430 --> 00:29:39,460
a lot recently, as far as
towards decentralization goes,

712
00:29:39,460 --> 00:29:40,610
is Mastodon.

713
00:29:40,610 --> 00:29:43,660
So obviously,
we're sitting here,

714
00:29:43,660 --> 00:29:46,960
this video at least
recorded in late 2022.

715
00:29:46,960 --> 00:29:50,870
And so Twitter is going
through a transformative time,

716
00:29:50,870 --> 00:29:51,830
to say the least.

717
00:29:51,830 --> 00:29:53,650
And that's obviously
putting a lot of--

718
00:29:53,650 --> 00:29:55,880
or shining a lot
of light on, well,

719
00:29:55,880 --> 00:29:59,670
what are the downsides or risks
of us having centralized, again,

720
00:29:59,670 --> 00:30:04,310
our internet or our
microblogging communications

721
00:30:04,310 --> 00:30:07,490
to a few major apps,
a few major players?

722
00:30:07,490 --> 00:30:10,170
And so Mastodon
encourages an alternative.

723
00:30:10,170 --> 00:30:12,750
It is a decentralized
social media platform.

724
00:30:12,750 --> 00:30:15,720
And also, full disclosure, I
do not have a Mastodon account.

725
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:17,880
I am not pushing for Mastodon.

726
00:30:17,880 --> 00:30:20,700
I have no interest or stake
in their future success.

727
00:30:20,700 --> 00:30:23,007
But I think it proposes
an interesting alternative

728
00:30:23,007 --> 00:30:24,840
to these, and that's
why I'm introducing it.

729
00:30:24,840 --> 00:30:28,820
But either way, what they mean
by decentralized social media

730
00:30:28,820 --> 00:30:31,620
platform is that the
software for Mastodon,

731
00:30:31,620 --> 00:30:34,970
the actual underlying code,
is completely open source.

732
00:30:34,970 --> 00:30:38,750
And what that means then is that
you can host your own Mastodon

733
00:30:38,750 --> 00:30:40,920
server on whatever
resources you want to.

734
00:30:40,920 --> 00:30:42,750
You could do it
on AWS resources,

735
00:30:42,750 --> 00:30:45,260
or you could do it on a
set of Raspberry Pis you

736
00:30:45,260 --> 00:30:47,240
have sitting at your house.

737
00:30:47,240 --> 00:30:50,280
And that server, as long as
it's connected to the internet,

738
00:30:50,280 --> 00:30:52,370
can still connect to and
follow other accounts

739
00:30:52,370 --> 00:30:54,050
that are on different servers.

740
00:30:54,050 --> 00:30:57,180
For that matter, you could have
your friends all share a server,

741
00:30:57,180 --> 00:31:00,552
but then remotely connect
to-- or follow other accounts

742
00:31:00,552 --> 00:31:01,260
on other servers.

743
00:31:01,260 --> 00:31:03,300
So it still looks like
a single feed to you.

744
00:31:03,300 --> 00:31:07,370
But the actual location or
the source of the information

745
00:31:07,370 --> 00:31:09,510
is coming from
different locations.

746
00:31:09,510 --> 00:31:12,860
This ensures, then,
that, well, whatever

747
00:31:12,860 --> 00:31:17,810
happens with the overarching
platform isn't technically going

748
00:31:17,810 --> 00:31:20,460
